  <h2>Five Mind-Blowing Fun Facts About Computers</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>🐛 <strong>The First Computer Bug:</strong> In 1947, a famous computer scientist named Grace Hopper found her computer wasn't working. When she opened it up, she found a real moth stuck inside a switch! Since then, errors in programs have been called "bugs."</li>
    <li>🚀 <strong>Moon Power:</strong> The smartphone in your hand (or your parent's hand) is over 100 million times more powerful than the computers NASA used to send astronauts to the Moon in 1969!</li>
    <li>🏠 <strong>Weight Watchers:</strong> The earliest computers built in the 1940s (like the ENIAC) were so massive they filled an entire room, weighed as much as 6 elephants (30 tons), and used massive amounts of electricity!</li>
    <li>🧮 <strong>Human Computers:</strong> Long ago, the word "computer" didn't mean a machine. It was a job title for a person whose job was to do math calculations all day!</li>
    <li>🥪 <strong>Silicon Sandwiches:</strong> Computer chips are made of silicon, which is refined from silica—the main ingredient in ordinary beach sand!</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-section">
    <h3>Do computers sleep or get tired?</h3>
    <p>
      Computers don't get tired like humans do because they are made of electrical circuits, not muscles. However, when you leave a computer on for a long time, it can gather temporary files in its RAM that slow it down. Putting a computer to "sleep" saves power, and restarting it clears out the temporary clutter so it runs fresh!
    </p>

    <h3>Can a computer get a real sickness or cold?</h3>
    <p>
      Computers cannot catch human colds or flu. But they can get "computer viruses," which are actually just bad software programs written by hackers to steal files or break systems. You can protect computers from viruses by using antivirus software and never clicking on strange links.
    </p>

    <h3>Why do computers use fans?</h3>
    <p>
      When electricity flows through the tiny components inside a computer, it creates heat. If the components get too hot, they can melt or stop working. Fans blow cool air over metal plates called heat sinks to keep the CPU, GPU, and other parts at a safe, cool temperature.
    </p>

    <h3>Is a smart refrigerator a computer?</h3>
    <p>
      Yes! Any device that can take input (like you selecting a temperature), process it, and control hardware is a computer. Smart fridges contain embedded computers that manage cooling, track grocery lists, and even display recipes on a screen.
    </p>
  </div>

